post_text:
CHS Football plays at Hugo this Friday night at 7 pm.

After visiting with their principal, we have learned that they have a small set of visitor bleachers that hold 360 people in normal situation (no social distancing). They have been gracious enough to offer to allow fans to sit in lawn chairs on the track to help with social distancing.

For those who cannot make the road trip, I found a website www.hugofootball.com that has a link at the top that says "Watch games here..." This link will take you to a radio station's Facebook page that covers Hugo games.

The stadium is a few blocks north of the school.
The address of the stadium is: 208 N 2nd St, Hugo, OK 74743

https://www.google.com/maps/place/Hugo+City+Sch+Football+Stadium/@34.0171228,-95.5113098,993m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m12!1m6!3m5!1s0x864ae9cf23900171:0xa2859dd1a11dd4e4!2sHugo+High+School!8m2!3d34.0148897!4d-95.5107224!3m4!1s0x864ae9ce387c2e0f:0xc6abb973ccd567e9!8m2!3d34.0175758!4d-95.510695

Please stay safe!!! I hope this is helpful for our fans to support our Wildcats!!!

It's a great day to be a WILDCAT!!!

Thinking about virtual school? Great. Please do not take your kids out of your district. When we do that, the district that you enroll in (even if it is an online platform like Epic) gets all of the funding for your child for the entire year.

Go with your district‚Äôs virtual plan.
We do not want our local public school to have to suffer and let teachers permanently go for this temporary problem.

Staying enrolled in your district ensures that the district is still strong when you return to brick and mortar schools.

post_text: There has been some who have had questions concerning masks at school. While it is highly recommended by the health care community and by our state officials to wear masks, CPS has not mandated masks for students at school at this time. CPS will require bus riders to wear mask due to the limited space on our buses and once school begins visitors who have appointments will be required to wear mask upon entering the building to protect our students and staff. We do realize that there may come a point in time where masks will be required in public schools and we recommend families consider preparing for this situation as it develops.

Checotah Public Schools is working diligently to prepare for the 2020-2021 school year. We are working on guidelines and protocols to provide solid educational services while also assuring we can offer the safest possible environment for students and staff. We will offer the following pathways for receiving instruction in the fall of 2020:

Traditional In-School classes-- Offered for PK-12 will be on campus setting and students will attend classes as usual with extra precautions taken to limit exposure to the COVID19 virus. This is considered the most effective form of instruction, however as needed, schools may move to Distance Learning when the situations arise.

Blended/Distance‚Ä¶

post_text:
Good morning CHS!!! Tomorrow is graduation!!!
Seniors: We will meet with small groups of seniors to do a walk through practice from 10:15 to 12:30 at the football field. The walk through should take about 10 minutes. Please come and do your session then leave, we cannot have students hanging around after the walk through.

Friday evening, please be on the field ready to start at 6:45, with your caps and gowns on. You may not have any extra decor on your cap or gown. Graduation starts at 7pm

Guests and families: We encourage seating in both sets of stands. Only seniors and staff will be allowed on the field. Please do not try to come on to the field or track.

EVERYONE: Please take social distance and health safety precautions. We have had an increase in cases in the area and we wish to follow provide the ceremony as safe as possible.

Thank you!!

Valedictorians and Salutatorian: Practice tonight at 5!!!

While the current pandemic situation is improving, it is with sadness we announce that Checotah High School is cancelling prom for this year. In reviewing the procedures, we are implementing to slowly open our school and community in a way that allows us to reach our goals of face to face instruction in August. It is not a reasonable decision to host an indoor extra curricular event of this magnitude that involves so many students, staff, visitors, and vendors from outside of our area to an event that does not allow for social distancing, and by nature is not conducive of following the guidelines we are still expected to maintain at this time.

Checotah High School will be recommending to‚Ä¶

The following information was released from Oklahoma Regents of Higher Education:

Oklahoma‚Äôs Promise: Alert for 10th-Grade Parents With Recent Income Loss

https://www.okhighered.org/okpromise/

If your student is or was in the 10th grade during the 2019-20 school year and you anticipate that your 2020 income may be under the $55,000 application limit for the Oklahoma‚Äôs Promise scholarship due to recent reductions in your income, you may submit an application based on your 2020 estimated income. The application must be submitted prior to the June 30, 2020, deadline. You will be required to provide a copy of your 2020 federal tax return when completed to verify that your 2020 income was under $55,000. The application will be held as pending until the tax documentation is received. Please send any questions to okpromise@osrhe.edu.

Good morning CHS!!!

Week 3 of Distance Learning, I want to say thank you and applaud our teachers for their hard work and dedication during this very unique time in education. Each one has had to learn new skills and embrace distance learning with very little time or training. They are doing a great job!

If you have a moment this week, have your students share what they are doing in their classes. I have seen interesting projects, unique art drawings, virtual field trips, puzzles, career exploration activities, and opportunities to share their thoughts on the life we are currently experiencing. There are some great activities that are helping our teenagers to continue to think, reason, read, write, create and grow as students. THANK YOU TEACHERS!!! WE TRULY APPRECIATE YOU!

To begin this week, we have our very talented band director, Mr Jim Davis, performing our National Anthem.

Good morning CHS!!

Today I want to give a huge shoutout to those who chose to be essential to our school and community by leaving their safe homes to come to the school to plan, prepare, pack, and deliver the meals that are going out to our students. While yesterday was not perfect, we should not forget to be thankful for our child nutrition workers, bus drivers, and support staff who get up, show up, and work tirelessly to provide this program to our students and families. I am positive it will be better next week, but more importantly I can assure you that none of it is possible without these great staff members and all they do and sacrifice to make this great feat occur.... So today, I say THANK YOU!!!

Now to bring a smile to your face and to start your day in song, we have Chloe Smith singing our National Anthem. Thank you Chloe for making our day a little brighter!!

2020 CNAY-Columbia Summer Scholarship

The Center for Native American Youth, in partnership with Columbia University‚Äôs Summer Immersion Program for High School Students, is offering one full-tuition, residential scholarship for a Native student to attend a 3-week pre-college program during summer 2020 in New York City.

The CNAY-Columbia scholarship covers the cost of housing, tuition, weekday meals, coursework materials, and other required student services. The estimated value of the scholarship is over $10,000.

APPLICATION DEADLINE: Due on February 28, 2020 at 11:59 pm Eastern Time.

Check out our website for more information and how to apply:

shared_text:
Delicia Hurst is with Sherry D. Marks.
February 18 at 7:00 PM ¬∑

Checotah Friends

This year will be the fourth award of the Jerry Don Hurst Memorial Scholarship.

The $500 scholarship will be awarded to a Checotah senior who plans to attend college or a trade/technical school.

Please help me get the word out to Checotah seniors. The application should be posted to the high school website shortly, and I believe there should be hard copy applications in English class. Deadline to submit all information is April 2nd.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî-
In 1991, Jerry Don Hurst started the second week of his senior year at Checotah high school. One evening after school, unbeknownst to him, he was given a poison laced drink containing potassium cyanide by two classmates. He died within minutes of taking a sip of the drink. Both classmates were convicted of murder and sentenced to prison.

This scholarship was created to honor the life of Jerry Don Hurst and to bring awareness to the topic of bullying. We must remember every action has a consequence; these consequences can be life altering.

Parents, please take some time over this Thanksgiving break to look through pictures with your seniors. Our video editing class would love to put together a collection of memories for the class of 2020.

The video starts with showing individual baby photos, followed by their senior photo. It will then have a section to show their years attending Marshall, Intermediate, Middle school, followed by their High school years.

The video editing class cannot complete this project without the help of parents. It is imperative that the deadlines be met for this project. This is a learning process for the students in the video editing class. The students are learning many skills with this project and‚Ä¶

post_text:
Today has been a busy day at CHS!!! Students throughout the day visited the booths at the Battle of Honey Springs. The Re-enactment is on Saturday, there is a lot to see and learn, I recommend the adventure if you have time this weekend. Thank you to the many volunteers that make this event possible. Also thank you to the teachers and staff that helped with days trip.

To end the day, Wildcat fans traveled to Roland for a very cold night of football which ended with a 33-8 victory over the Rangers. Thank you to the fans, the band, the cheerleaders, and our great student section for bearing through the chill to support our Wildcats on the field. Congratulations to Wildcat football team for a big win!!! Next week is senior night and a home game against Lincoln Christian. Let‚Äôs go Wildcats, beat the Bulldogs!!
